which is represented by four hexadecimal codes

00:12:40.600 --> 00:12:43.640
which represent the letters A, B, C, and D.

00:12:44.560 --> 00:12:48.959
I was already started and I was so excited.

00:12:49.399 --> 00:12:52.640
So I was able to plug that into a piece of code that says,

00:12:53.480 --> 00:12:56.760
okay, when I press some data, you see,

00:12:57.120 --> 00:13:01.397
the hat itself has 12 little nodes where I can attach

00:13:01.480 --> 00:13:02.480
an electrode.

00:13:02.639 --> 00:13:05.436
And each of these electrodes can correspond to a member

00:13:05.519 --> 00:13:06.239
of a list.

00:13:06.519 --> 00:13:09.477
So I can parse each electrode and tell it,

00:13:09.560 --> 00:13:11.640
depending on which one is pressed,

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:15.040
pass onto that the corresponding key.

00:13:15.480 --> 00:13:17.116
So, if the first one is pressed,

00:13:17.199 --> 00:13:18.800
press add the left key.

00:13:19.160 --> 00:13:22.519
If the second one is pressed, put in the right key.

00:13:22.839 --> 00:13:26.160
And then up, and then down, and so on and so forth.

00:13:26.440 --> 00:13:27.316
So when I did that,

00:13:27.399 --> 00:13:31.600
I ended up with an array of touched codes.

00:13:31.959 --> 00:13:34.797
Now, you might notice this allows me to press more than

00:13:34.880 --> 00:13:36.239
one at the same time

00:13:36.600 --> 00:13:39.277
because with DDR, there might be sometimes where we

00:13:39.360 --> 00:13:40.756
might be doing a little bit of this,

00:13:40.839 --> 00:13:41.880
a little bit of that.

00:13:42.279 --> 00:13:44.320
So it's good to have.

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:46.160
Once I've done that,

00:13:46.480 --> 00:13:48.720
I need to actually build a keystroke

00:13:48.880 --> 00:13:50.837
because as you saw earlier,

00:13:50.920 --> 00:13:53.280
it's made up of eight hexadecimal codes.

00:13:53.800 --> 00:13:58.797
So, the first two are made up of modifiers.

00:13:58.880 --> 00:14:00.196
So we'll skip those,

00:14:00.279 --> 00:14:01.957
and then I'll just put in the rest of the keys

00:14:02.040 --> 00:14:03.116
and put in a bunch of zeros

00:14:03.199 --> 00:14:05.960
just so it makes up a nice list of eight.

00:14:06.560 --> 00:14:07.840
Once I do that,

00:14:08.040 --> 00:14:10.560
I can actually start the script,

00:14:10.880 --> 00:14:12.160
plug in my Raspberry Pi,

00:14:12.519 --> 00:14:14.560
and start just looking at what's coming out.

00:14:14.880 --> 00:14:18.280
And you'll see I get a nice little A, or a B,

00:14:18.639 --> 00:14:20.957
or a C, or a C and a D, and all that.

00:14:21.040 --> 00:14:24.960
So, next up is converting that into a byte array.

00:14:25.279 --> 00:14:27.957
Now, again, documentation, super helpful,

00:14:28.040 --> 00:14:31.199
MDN allowed me to find this function here called

00:14:31.800 --> 00:14:32.280
𝚄𝚒𝚗𝚝𝟾𝙰𝚛𝚛𝚊𝚢.

00:14:32.680 --> 00:14:33.316
And from that,

00:14:33.399 --> 00:14:37.357
I was able to create a keystroke from that

00:14:37.440 --> 00:14:38.720
that is a byte array.

00:14:39.240 --> 00:14:46.520
Next, I got to send that over to the computer.

00:14:46.880 --> 00:14:50.200
